{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"124"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/124"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.27,0.07,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"124"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/124"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"124"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice on bowel cancer screening. She has no symptoms of concern, however, is concerned since her father was diagnosed with carcinoma of the rectum at the age of 65 years. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FOBT every two years starting now","FOBT every two years starting at the age of 50","Colonoscopy now","Colonoscopy at the age of 50","Refer for genetic risk assessment"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScreening recommendations are based on the lifetime risk of colorectal cancer (CRC) and should be determined by the number and type of relatives affected by CRC as well as their age of diagnosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EFOBT every two years starting now\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate advice for this patient. This recommendation aligns with the general population screening guidelines, as the patient\u0027s family history does not significantly increase her risk (i.e. she is Category 1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EColorectal screening guidelines and risk stratification were updated in September 2023. The current risk categories and screening recommendations are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk, without known hereditary cancer syndrome\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFOBT every two years starting at the age of 50\u003C/strong\u003E were the previous screening recommendations for the general population, however this has been brought forward to commence at age 45 in the most recent update of guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy now\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a first-line screening tool for individuals at average risk. It carries risks and is more invasive than FOBT, which is sufficient for initial screening in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy at the age of 50\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if the FOBT results are positive or if there were other risk factors, but it\u0027s not the most appropriate first-line screening method for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for genetic risk assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for individuals with a stronger family history of CRC, such as multiple affected first-degree relatives or relatives diagnosed at a very young age. In this case, with only one first-degree relative diagnosed at age 65, genetic risk assessment is not necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["General screening recommendations for colorectal cancer is a biennial FOBT from the age of 45","For those with a single first-degree relative with colorectal cancer, risk stratification is based on whether the relative was diagnosed before the age of 60","High-risk individuals for colorectal cancer require referral to genetic risk assessment."],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"124"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T20:45:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T19:04:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"124"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"positio